{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aaccbfc8-7f92-47d9-b798-00467ca5b89b","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Recursive wildcard glob (`**\\*.*`)\n**Line 9 in `.csproj`** — `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>` forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is the single most expensive evaluation pattern; cost grows linearly with file count.\n\n## 2. File I/O via property function\n**Line 13** — `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` performs disk I/O *during evaluation*. Property functions that read files block the evaluation phase and can't be cached across re-evaluations.\n\n## 3. Deeply chained imports (3 levels)\n`EvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props` — each import adds an XML parse + evaluation pass. While 3 levels is moderate, this pattern scales poorly and increases evaluation time linearly with depth.\n\n### Recommendations\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Narrow the pattern (e.g., specific extensions) or move to a target so it runs only during build, not evaluation |\n| `ReadAllText` in property | Move file reading into a target/task that executes at build time |\n| Nested imports | Flatten into a single `.props` file where possible |\n\nThe glob and `ReadAllText` are the most impactful — they turn a fast in-memory evaluation into something that hits the filesystem repeatedly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6c2a106d-9395-44f1-8c75-7cf164a79796","outputTokens":364,"requestId":"2841:71DA5:2CDEEA:344BC1:69FA95E6"},"id":"811d997b-ca50-40e8-9d5a-09799ab87518","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:14:27.635Z","parentId":"27be2681-90fa-4269-ac55-8be5a3e10e46"}
